WEBVTT

00:02.503 --> 00:04.744
MOHINDER:
Previously on Heroes.

00:05.840 --> 00:07.046
(SPEAKING JAPANESE)

00:07.133 --> 00:08.418
You are supposed
to be a hero.

00:08.885 --> 00:10.250
(EXCLAIMS IN PAIN)

00:10.344 --> 00:11.925
I don't think
she wants to be
my princess.

00:12.305 --> 00:14.842
Dr. Suresh,
can we count you in?

00:14.932 --> 00:16.342
MOH/NDER ON PHONE:
They finally took the bait.

00:16.434 --> 00:18.550
They caught up
with me in Cairo.
I'm in.

00:18.644 --> 00:21.556
And you and |wi|| bring
this whole company down.

00:21.939 --> 00:25.352
We are all in grave danger.
Our past has caught up
with us.

00:25.443 --> 00:26.853
No!

00:27.486 --> 00:29.192
I'm West.
Claire.

00:29.280 --> 00:32.113
Are you one of them
or one of the others?

00:32.366 --> 00:35.199
I figured you'd
rather have a real one.

00:36.037 --> 00:37.026
(SCREAMING)

00:37.121 --> 00:38.110
MATT: We have to talk
about the nightmares.

00:38.206 --> 00:39.241
There's nothing
you can do.

00:39.332 --> 00:41.243
Molly, I wanna help you.

00:46.047 --> 00:47.787
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

00:48.299 --> 00:49.960
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

00:50.968 --> 00:52.219
RICKY: What the hell
are you doing here?

00:52.303 --> 00:54.009
Who are you?
What's your name?

00:54.096 --> 00:55.131
I don't know.

00:56.140 --> 00:57.471
(SCREAMS)

01:03.481 --> 01:04.812
(EXHALES)

01:06.692 --> 01:07.977
(GRUNTS)

01:09.946 --> 01:11.311
He's awake.

01:12.490 --> 01:13.821
Where am I?

01:16.118 --> 01:17.324
(GASPS)

01:17.703 --> 01:18.818
Home.

01:19.538 --> 01:21.665
You took something
that's ours, boyo.

01:22.875 --> 01:25.662
Just tell us
where you stashed
the iPods.

01:26.671 --> 01:29.663
We'll cut your binds.
You'll be on your way.

01:30.675 --> 01:33.508
As square a deal
as you're likely to find.

01:34.345 --> 01:36.586
I didn't take anything.

01:36.681 --> 01:37.921
Right.

01:38.015 --> 01:42.600
With the thousands
of shipping containers coming
through Cork Harbor every day,

01:42.687 --> 01:47.272
you just happened to be
having tea in the one
we were set to rob.

01:48.484 --> 01:50.816
I don't know
how I got in there.

01:51.362 --> 01:54.195
You might wanna consider
remembering, boyo.

01:54.282 --> 01:56.068
You're in a bad spot.

02:11.215 --> 02:14.958
(GRUNTS) Dang it all,
my wedding ring
fell in with the eggs.

02:28.816 --> 02:31.398
We do have
a colander, dear.

02:31.485 --> 02:33.100
No need to be flashy.

02:33.738 --> 02:35.399
It's no big deal.

02:36.407 --> 02:38.648
It isn't until
it gets you noticed.

02:38.743 --> 02:40.153
I can't even be
myself at home?

02:40.244 --> 02:42.656
It's bad enough
that l have to be
all fake at school.

02:43.039 --> 02:45.246
MR. BENNET:
I simply asked
you to lay Iow.

02:46.751 --> 02:48.241
High school
doesn't work
like that, Dad.

02:48.336 --> 02:51.078
You lay low,
and you get noticed
more than anyone.

02:51.172 --> 02:54.164
They have metal detectors
for people who lay too low.

02:54.258 --> 02:56.089
l have to be someone.

02:57.428 --> 02:59.669
You know I trust you, Claire.
I mean, we got you
your own car.

02:59.764 --> 03:02.380
You know, it may be
easy for you to pretend

03:02.475 --> 03:04.591
that you're the most
boring photocopier
in the world,

03:04.685 --> 03:06.596
but I can't not
be what I am.

03:06.854 --> 03:07.843
Whatever that is.

03:07.938 --> 03:09.929
Making copies
is not my job.

03:10.107 --> 03:11.847
Keeping this family safe
is myjob.

03:11.942 --> 03:14.354
And if that means I don't
have time to make you
breakfast in the morning

03:14.445 --> 03:16.106
or l have to dress up
in this stupid shirt

03:16.197 --> 03:19.405
so that we stay invisible
and nobody finds us,

03:19.492 --> 03:21.483
then that's what I'll do.

03:22.536 --> 03:24.788
And I need you
to do the same.

03:27.458 --> 03:28.789
(SIGHING)

03:29.960 --> 03:33.202
I forgot how weird
it must be for you to
play normal after being

03:33.631 --> 03:35.212
whatever that was.

03:35.341 --> 03:37.548
Don't you feel
sorry for your dad.

03:37.635 --> 03:39.341
Compared to the life I had,

03:40.596 --> 03:42.382
normal is a pretty
nice vacation.

03:45.810 --> 03:47.801
Thanks.
You're welcome.

03:48.521 --> 03:50.136
Have a good day.

04:03.994 --> 04:05.655
Did you see this?

04:10.000 --> 04:11.991
MR. BENNET:
I knew this would happen.

04:13.045 --> 04:14.080
Kaito.

04:14.171 --> 04:15.377
How'd you know
this was gonna happen?

04:16.841 --> 04:20.504
Hey, that's not the way
we do things anymore.

04:21.303 --> 04:23.339
No more secrets.

04:23.806 --> 04:25.467
That was the deal.

04:29.061 --> 04:32.724
This was done by
a very gifted artist
in New York. lsaac Mendez.

04:32.815 --> 04:35.682
Everything he's
ever painted
has come true.

04:37.236 --> 04:40.820
Except for a series of eight.
I was only given the first.

04:41.031 --> 04:43.283
There're seven more?
What's in the other paintings?

04:43.367 --> 04:44.868
I don't know.

04:49.832 --> 04:51.788
But I'm gonna find them.

04:53.502 --> 04:55.367
(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

04:55.463 --> 04:57.044
(CHATTERING)

04:59.925 --> 05:01.461
What, you waiting
on an invitation?

05:01.552 --> 05:02.632
Oh, no.

05:02.887 --> 05:04.502
ljust spent so much time
on that side of the tape,

05:04.597 --> 05:06.053
l was just savoring
the moment. That's all.

05:06.140 --> 05:08.131
Yeah, well, welcome
to the big leagues,
Detective.

05:08.225 --> 05:09.761
Let's hope you survive.

05:09.852 --> 05:13.561
All right,
Kaito Nakamura, 70.
Japanese national.

05:13.647 --> 05:15.979
CEO of
Yamagato Industries.

05:16.066 --> 05:20.685
Now, he fell out of the sky
onto Central Park West
with this in his pocket.

05:20.779 --> 05:22.519
That look familiar?

05:24.283 --> 05:26.615
No. No, I've never
seen this before.

05:26.702 --> 05:28.988
Well, Mr. Masahashi here
is a witness.

05:29.079 --> 05:31.536
He says that he saw
Mr. Nakamura being pushed

05:31.624 --> 05:32.830
by someone
who went over
with him.

05:32.917 --> 05:34.327
But we've only got one body.

05:34.418 --> 05:37.581
Well, either the killer
fell 20 stories, got up
and walked away,

05:37.671 --> 05:39.207
or flew away.

05:39.298 --> 05:41.334
You know somebody
who can do that?

05:45.346 --> 05:46.335
(EXCLAIMS)

05:46.430 --> 05:48.921
We found a fingerprint
on the photo.

05:50.392 --> 05:51.768
Got a match.

05:52.645 --> 05:55.728
Angela Petrelli.
We need to bring her
right in.

06:01.946 --> 06:03.436
Mr. Masahashi.

06:05.449 --> 06:07.861
You ever seen
this symbol before?

06:08.869 --> 06:13.112
Yes, it is a kanji.
It means "great ability."

06:13.374 --> 06:14.363
"Godsend."

06:14.458 --> 06:15.493
Ability?

06:15.668 --> 06:19.377
It is the crest
of Takezo Kensei,
a famous hero in Japan.

06:19.463 --> 06:23.627
Mr. Nakamura used to read
the Kensei stories
to his son, Hiro.

06:24.635 --> 06:26.000
I need to talk to him.

06:26.595 --> 06:27.971
So do |.

06:41.318 --> 06:42.854
(HEN CACKLING)

06:46.198 --> 06:47.984
(SPEAKING JAPANESE)

06:55.833 --> 06:57.414
(FLIES BUZZING)

06:57.501 --> 06:58.866
(SIGHING)

07:04.008 --> 07:05.248
You must be sober!

07:05.342 --> 07:08.425
If we don't go after
Yaeko right now,
she'll be killed!

07:08.512 --> 07:09.501
Who's Yaeko?

07:09.597 --> 07:12.009
The girl you're supposed
to fall in love with.

07:12.099 --> 07:13.214
The one who hates me?

07:13.309 --> 07:16.176
Yes, before I came
back in time
and ruined everything,

07:16.270 --> 07:19.433
she was supposed to be
your princess, and you,
a hero.

07:20.858 --> 07:22.268
You look like a fish
when you talk.

07:22.359 --> 07:24.020
No. I promise,
if you do this,

07:24.111 --> 07:27.023
they will tell the story
for 400 years, minimum.

07:27.114 --> 07:28.820
Like a giant carp.

07:31.327 --> 07:33.192
(SPEAKING JAPANESE)

07:36.373 --> 07:37.704
(GASPS)

07:55.643 --> 07:56.803
(SPEAKING JAPANESE)

07:57.978 --> 07:59.013
(CHUCKLES)

07:59.104 --> 08:00.560
(WHOOPING)

08:14.286 --> 08:17.528
This video demonstrates
the newt's amazing ability

08:17.623 --> 08:20.615
to regrow
a completely
working limb.

08:20.709 --> 08:23.325
But newts are not
the only creatures
with this talent.

08:23.420 --> 08:26.958
Thanks to millions of years
of combined mutation,

08:27.049 --> 08:30.416
lizards are capable
of cellular regeneration.

08:30.844 --> 08:32.505
You mean
like people who can
heal themselves?

08:32.596 --> 08:35.053
(SCOFFS) No. Not people,
Claire. Lizards.

08:35.140 --> 08:36.516
And raise your hand,
please.

08:39.937 --> 08:42.349
But it's possible, right,
for people to be able
to do that, too?

08:42.439 --> 08:43.940
I mean, theoretically.

08:44.024 --> 08:45.730
Well, there's a lot
of controversial,
though promising,

08:45.818 --> 08:47.058
work with stem cells.

08:47.152 --> 08:49.268
So we might be
able to culture
whole organs and limbs

08:49.363 --> 08:51.399
for people who need them.

08:52.116 --> 08:56.655
I'd guess the next step
for us is phasing out
the extra parts.

08:56.745 --> 08:58.701
We're not using
the appendix anymore

08:58.789 --> 09:00.871
or grinding bone
with our wisdom teeth.

09:00.958 --> 09:02.789
We don't even really need
a pinky toe for balance.

09:02.876 --> 09:05.583
It's all just
junk in our DNA.

09:05.671 --> 09:08.378
I've read that some people
might've evolved
a different code already.

09:08.465 --> 09:09.580
Is that possible?

09:09.675 --> 09:12.542
PROFESSOR: I'm afraid you
are gonna need an advanced
degree in genetics

09:12.636 --> 09:14.547
to get at those answers.

09:14.638 --> 09:17.095
And I hope you thank me
in your dissertation.

09:24.481 --> 09:25.641
(WHISPERING) What?

09:30.654 --> 09:33.111
Oh, so how'd you
like the jet?

09:33.198 --> 09:34.904
A lot better than
flying coach, huh?

09:34.992 --> 09:36.948
I didn't agree to work
with you for the comforts.

09:37.035 --> 09:39.242
Still, it doesn't hurt.

09:39.329 --> 09:40.865
I can't help people
with abilities

09:40.956 --> 09:43.117
unless I have access
to all your records
and your labs.

09:43.208 --> 09:44.243
Of course, of course.

09:44.334 --> 09:47.076
And right now I need
to get you back
on that plane

09:47.171 --> 09:49.913
because I have
your first assignment
here.

09:50.007 --> 09:51.087
Assignment?

09:51.175 --> 09:53.461
I thought you said
your company kept its
medical samples here.

09:53.552 --> 09:55.918
Not samples. A man.

09:56.013 --> 09:58.049
In Port-au-Prince,
he turned up sick.

09:58.140 --> 10:01.598
Weakness, tremors,
loss of abilities.

10:01.685 --> 10:02.800
He's dying.

10:02.895 --> 10:04.010
The virus?
Mmm-hmm.

10:04.104 --> 10:06.516
If there's another case,
there could be some
reservoir of infection.

10:06.607 --> 10:08.268
That's what I need
you to find out.

10:08.358 --> 10:11.020
To date, there have been
only two presentations
of the disease,

10:11.111 --> 10:14.444
your sister in 1974
and Molly Walker
four months ago.

10:14.531 --> 10:16.487
If there is actually
a third case...

10:16.575 --> 10:17.781
Then it is spreading.

10:17.868 --> 10:18.948
l'll test him.

10:19.036 --> 10:20.526
If it's true,
I'll bring him back
as soon as possible.

10:21.580 --> 10:23.662
Oh, and Doctor,

10:23.749 --> 10:27.367
as of now,
your blood is the only
cure for that virus.

10:27.795 --> 10:29.535
Try not to get
yourself killed.

10:34.676 --> 10:36.052
(EXHALES)

10:36.470 --> 10:38.256
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

11:57.509 --> 11:59.124
(DOOR CREAKING)

12:04.099 --> 12:06.511
Bet you were
prettier yesterday.

12:07.311 --> 12:10.098
I like your necklace.
What does it mean?

12:11.648 --> 12:13.263
I wish I knew.

12:13.609 --> 12:16.271
Let's try an easier one.
What's your name?

12:16.653 --> 12:17.813
I don't know.

12:18.363 --> 12:20.103
It's not your day, is it?

12:20.198 --> 12:22.814
l'm Caitlin.
You know that much now.

12:26.163 --> 12:27.152
Caitlin?

12:27.247 --> 12:28.487
Mmm-hmm.

12:30.167 --> 12:31.373
What are they
gonna do to me?

12:31.460 --> 12:33.917
I don't know.
Whatever my brother
thinks is best.

12:34.004 --> 12:35.494
Your brother?

12:36.340 --> 12:38.080
Did he send you in here?

12:38.175 --> 12:40.006
He'd pitch an epic fit.

12:40.093 --> 12:42.379
Thought I'd try
a kinder tack.

12:43.180 --> 12:47.344
Thing is, this job,
it's bigger than you
and a couple of quid.

12:47.809 --> 12:49.720
They pulled it for
this man named McSorley.

12:49.978 --> 12:51.514
Promised delivery today.

12:53.357 --> 12:56.099
So what happens
if this guy doesn't get
what he wants?

12:56.944 --> 13:00.528
You have to remember
something, anything.
A name. A face.

13:02.783 --> 13:06.025
First thing I remember is
your brother and his crew
finding me.

13:07.245 --> 13:08.576
Then the big guy
came at me, and...

13:08.664 --> 13:12.498
And then an electrical shock
blew Tuko on his arse.
I heard the story.

13:12.584 --> 13:14.199
The spark.

13:15.420 --> 13:17.456
I think it came from me.

13:17.547 --> 13:19.003
(SCOFFS)

13:19.091 --> 13:21.127
My hand.

13:23.929 --> 13:25.669
I know that it seems...

13:25.764 --> 13:26.970
It's impossible!

13:29.726 --> 13:32.217
I've just wrung out
a lot of your blood.

13:35.232 --> 13:37.393
You don't have
a mark on you.

13:49.037 --> 13:50.823
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

14:14.438 --> 14:16.099
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

14:49.598 --> 14:51.589
I do not want
your cure.

14:53.852 --> 14:55.388
Without it you could die.

14:55.479 --> 14:57.060
God gave me a power.

14:57.147 --> 14:59.433
| abused his gift,
so he took it away.

14:59.941 --> 15:01.932
Now I suffer
his judgment.

15:02.027 --> 15:04.143
Then perhaps we should
leave it to God to decide.

15:04.237 --> 15:07.729
Chances are you carry one
of a hundred viruses
I can do nothing about.

15:07.824 --> 15:11.316
If you somehow carry
this one virus,
there is only one cure.

15:11.411 --> 15:15.370
A distillation
of my own blood.
And l was guided to you.

15:15.457 --> 15:18.199
Surely that's a sign.
Just the same
as your suffering.

15:18.293 --> 15:19.794
A sign of what?

15:19.878 --> 15:22.711
That God isn't quite
done with you yet.

15:23.340 --> 15:27.709
So, my friend,
shall we see if he still
offers redemption?

15:34.017 --> 15:35.803
(SPEAKING SPANISH)

16:20.313 --> 16:21.723
(EXHALES)

16:28.989 --> 16:30.399
(MOANS)

16:41.376 --> 16:42.661
(PANTING)

16:59.978 --> 17:02.014
(HEALER SPEAKING SPANISH)

17:02.439 --> 17:03.975
(DOOR OPENING)

17:05.275 --> 17:06.640
(GRUNTS)

17:08.445 --> 17:10.231
(MEN LAUGHING)

17:10.906 --> 17:12.271
(GRUNTS)

17:13.283 --> 17:15.023
(SPEAKING JAPANESE)

17:24.252 --> 17:26.243
(HIRO SPEAKING JAPANESE)

17:51.196 --> 17:52.902
(ALL EXCLAIM)

18:00.247 --> 18:01.828
(HIRO LAUGHING)

18:07.045 --> 18:08.626
(HIRO LAUGHING)

18:56.261 --> 18:58.252
RICKY: Keep an eye on him.

18:58.346 --> 19:01.383
If he so much as lays
an inconsiderate fart,

19:01.474 --> 19:02.930
you grab the gun.

19:03.643 --> 19:05.224
What am I, 12?

19:06.813 --> 19:08.849
Always.

19:17.240 --> 19:18.696
(GRUNTING)

19:21.119 --> 19:22.905
(WHISPERING)
Come on. Come on.

19:31.588 --> 19:33.374
(EXHALES)

19:37.052 --> 19:38.633
(EXHALES)

19:54.235 --> 19:57.523
Sorry, fellas.
Ricky and the boys
just left.

20:02.994 --> 20:06.031
Aye, I saw.
We're not here
for Ricky.

20:07.123 --> 20:10.286
Lucky, then.
I've just tapped
a barrel. Two pints?

20:12.212 --> 20:14.578
No, thanks, love.
We came for you.

20:14.964 --> 20:16.215
(GRUNTS)

20:19.219 --> 20:20.254
(GRUNTS)

20:20.345 --> 20:21.926
(GUN COCKING)

20:27.477 --> 20:28.717
(GRUNTS)

20:29.229 --> 20:30.685
(SCREAMING)

20:35.110 --> 20:36.395
(SIGHING)

20:42.117 --> 20:43.402
(EXHALES)

20:47.622 --> 20:49.487
(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

20:49.624 --> 20:52.081
So, lizards, huh?

20:53.211 --> 20:56.203
Tell me you didn't
just time that so I'd walk
right past you.

20:56.297 --> 20:58.583
I figured you'd be more
into whales or something.

20:58.675 --> 20:59.755
Unicorns.

21:00.677 --> 21:03.089
You know, you make
a lot of assumptions.

21:03.346 --> 21:05.086
Is my hair really
that blonde?

21:05.515 --> 21:07.051
I think it's cool,
actually.

21:07.267 --> 21:09.258
I'm sort of
into genetics, too.

21:10.145 --> 21:12.101
Well, I didn't say
I was into genetics.

21:12.188 --> 21:15.055
You don't have to hide
everything interesting
aboutyou.

21:16.526 --> 21:19.268
Biology's supposed
to be our destiny,

21:19.362 --> 21:22.695
but people forget
genes can change.

21:23.575 --> 21:26.282
I thought guys like you
are supposed to sit
at the back

21:26.369 --> 21:28.109
of the classroom
and hate everything.

21:28.204 --> 21:29.193
| just found this book.

21:29.289 --> 21:31.496
It's by some Indian guy.
I can barely even
pronounce his name.

21:31.583 --> 21:34.620
It's about everything
you're talking about.

21:34.711 --> 21:37.327
People who've evolved.

21:37.422 --> 21:39.378
There's a whole chapter
on regeneration.

21:39.466 --> 21:44.381
Sorry, I left all my awesome
genetics textbook reading
for the summer vacation.

21:44.721 --> 21:46.257
You should see it.

21:46.347 --> 21:50.681
I could bring it over,
get you on your way
to your Ph.D.

21:50.768 --> 21:54.636
You know, I don't really
care that much. I was
just kind of bored in class.

21:54.731 --> 21:55.811
Really?

21:55.899 --> 21:59.858
Yes, but if you like lizards,
that's awesome, have fun,
and I gotta go home.

22:03.281 --> 22:04.771
Where's my car?

22:07.952 --> 22:09.488
(EXHALING)

22:12.582 --> 22:14.413
(HIRO SPEAKING JAPANESE)

22:40.360 --> 22:41.475
(EXCLAIMS)

22:41.569 --> 22:43.355
(HIRO SPEAKING JAPANESE)

22:51.621 --> 22:52.952
(GIGGLES)

22:57.001 --> 22:58.332
(LAUGHS)

23:23.903 --> 23:25.313
(CHUCKLES)

24:46.569 --> 24:48.730
MOHINDER: Your blood is
clearing the viral load.

24:48.905 --> 24:50.486
It seems you have
this disease after all.

24:51.240 --> 24:53.276
How are your hands?

24:55.411 --> 24:57.402
Steady as faith.

24:58.081 --> 24:59.821
I prayed your cure
would not work.

24:59.916 --> 25:01.781
Ifl prayed, lwould
have asked the same.

25:01.876 --> 25:04.709
The thought of this virus
finding you out here.

25:04.796 --> 25:06.002
If it spreads...

25:06.089 --> 25:10.583
So you did not believe
what you said, about God
sending you to cure me.

25:10.677 --> 25:14.169
I have trouble believing
in any god that would allow
a pathogen like this to exist.

25:14.263 --> 25:15.594
It killed my sister.

25:18.726 --> 25:21.012
Seems like it's becoming
even more virulent.

25:21.521 --> 25:25.184
With the replication rate
this aggressive, you would
have been dead by morning.

25:25.274 --> 25:28.016
The people I work with
will want me to bring you
in for observation.

25:28.111 --> 25:29.772
I have a plane.

25:31.864 --> 25:33.445
You work for people?

25:33.950 --> 25:35.156
A company.

25:36.452 --> 25:39.410
Of course.
There is always
a company.

25:46.629 --> 25:50.087
Where is he?
Where is the Haitian?

25:50.466 --> 25:53.378
A Haitian.
Isn't he in Haiti?

25:53.469 --> 25:54.800
We're in Haiti.

25:55.430 --> 25:58.046
You've been out
of contact for hours.

25:59.058 --> 26:00.639
I was in your office.

26:00.727 --> 26:03.810
You gave me an envelope,
said a man may have the virus,

26:03.896 --> 26:05.852
that I was to cure him.

26:06.649 --> 26:08.640
He wouldn't have been able
to take your memory

26:08.735 --> 26:10.726
unless the vaccine worked,

26:10.820 --> 26:13.402
so apparently it did.

26:13.489 --> 26:16.231
Full recovery.
Thank you,
Dr. Suresh.

26:16.993 --> 26:18.984
My memory...

26:20.371 --> 26:22.407
I'm sorry.

26:22.999 --> 26:25.081
Well, at least
we've contained
the virus.

26:25.168 --> 26:28.535
We'll just chalk this up
to a rookie mistake.

